#Text=George Paulet ( 1553 – 1608 )
#Text=For the admiral , see Lord George Paulet .

#Text=Sir George Paulet ( 1553 – 1608 ) , also known as Pawlet or Powlet , was an English soldier , administrator , and governor of Derry who was killed by the followers of Sir Cahir O'Dogherty during O'Doherty 's Rebellion .
#Text=After his death , Paulet 's command at Derry was burned to the ground by the rebels . [ 1 ]
#Text=Paulet was knighted in 1607 . [ 2 ]
#Text=Early life

#Text=He was a son of Sir George Paulet ( died 1558 ) of Crondall , Hampshire , brother of William Paulet , 1st Marquess of Winchester , and his third wife , Elizabeth , daughter of William Windsor , 2nd Baron Windsor . [ 3 ] [ 4 ]
#Text=Paulet was educated at Eton , 1564 – 72 , and at King 's College , Cambridge , 1572-5 . [ 5 ]
#Text=Early career
#Text=His contemporaries call George a gentleman of Hampshire .
#Text=The king 's letters of 20 and 23 July 1606 , directing his appointment to the governorship of Derry , speak of his service in the wars . [ 1 ]
#Text=One of the oldest depictions of fort Derry , Ireland .
#Text=Derry was sacked and burned by the O'Doherty & McDavitt clans in 1608 .
#Text=He began at Derry by buying land from the constable , Sir Henry Docwra , who had built a town there more than thirty years after the destruction of Randolph 's settlement .

#Text=Docwra incurred the hostility of Charles Blount , 8th Baron Mountjoy ( who became Earl of Devonshire ) , Lord Deputy of Ireland , by supporting Donnell Ballagh O'Cahan , Sir Cahir O'Doherty , and Niall Garve O'Donnell , who he thought had been ill-treated .

#Text=James I agreed with Devonshire on Irish policy , about the desirability of ruling Ulster through Hugh Ó Neill , 2nd Earl of Tyrone and Rory Ó Donnell , 1st Earl of Tyrconnell , without much regard for minor chiefs .
#Text=Devonshire died 3 April 1606 ; but he had previously approved the sale of Docwra 's property to Paulet , whom he knew well .
#Text=Docwra accordingly sold him his house , land which he had bought , and his company of foot , at a low price .
#Text=The vice-provostship of Derry was thrown in without extra charge . [ 1 ]

#Text=The new governor was established at Derry in the early winter of 1606 , and on 20 February following Sir Arthur Chichester , the new Lord Deputy , told Robert Cecil , 1st Earl of Salisbury that he was unfit for the place , and that there had been many dissensions since his arrival .
#Text=He fell out with George Montgomery , the new bishop of Derry , over land claims .

#Text=Tyrone and Tyrconnell fled from Ireland early in September 1607 ( the Flight of the Earls ) ; O'Cahan , who ruled the greater part of what is now County Londonderry , and of O'Doherty , the chief of Inishowen in County Donegal , came under some suspicion .
#Text=Docwra had tried to divide these chiefs from the Earls , but Paulet had his own ideas on handling them . [ 1 ]
#Text=O'Doherty put some armed men on Tory Island , but this seems to have been done with the consent of the few inhabitants .

#Text=Sir Richard Hansard , who commanded for the Plantation of Ulster at Lifford in Donegal , recounts that O'Dogherty left Burt Castle , on Lough Swilly , at the end of October to superintend the felling of timber for building ; but that this gave rise to a report that he was in rebellion .
#Text=He then began to arm about seventy followers , refusing all recruits from outside his own district .
#Text=Paulet made an unsuccessful attempt to seize Burt in the chief 's absence , and reported everything to Chichester .
#Text=O'Doherty remonstrated with him in a temperate letter ; Paulet then ( falsely ) denied strongly that he had ever intended to surprise Burt , and accused O'Doherty of treason .
#Text=O'Doherty went to Dublin early in December and made his excuses to Chichester , who accepted them , but without much confidence .

#Text=On 18 April the privy council ordered him to be fully restored to such of his ancestral lands as were still withheld , but this order did not reach the Irish government until he was actually in rebellion . [ 1 ]
#Text=O'Doherty 's Rebellion
#Text=Main article : Burning of Derry
#Text=The Annals of the Four Masters state that Paulet struck O'Doherty ; there is more support for the idea that Paulet provoked O'Doherty into rebellion by insults .
#Text=Paulet 's carelessness invited attack , though Chichester warned him repeatedly to keep good watch .
#Text=On the night of Monday , 18 April 1608 , O'Doherty , at the head of fewer than a hundred men , seized the outpost at Culmore by a trick , and surprised Derry itself an hour before daybreak .
#Text=Paulet was killed by O'Doherty 's foster-father Phelim Reagh MacDavitt , and the city was sacked and burned .
#Text=Sir Josias Bodley , not however an eye-witness , reported that Paulet fell fighting valiantly ; but the English government spoke of his cowardice .
#Text=Paulet had been warned by Richard Hansard , who held his own against the rebels at Lifford . [ 1 ]
#Text=Despite the early success at Derry , O'Doherty 's Rebellion was defeated by the swift response of the Dublin government .
#Text=A force was sent out which recovered the ruins of Derry and killed O'Doherty at the Battle of Kilmacrennan .
#Text=Marriage and issue
#Text=Paulet married Joan Kyme , daughter of Richard Kyme of Lewes , Sussex and Margery Humphrey .
#Text=They had a son and a daughter . [ 6 ] [ 7 ]
#Text=Frances Paulet , married Richard Mascall of South Malling , Sussex . [ 7 ]
#Text=His wife was with him at Derry , and the contemporary tract Newes from Ireland concerning the late treacherous Action ; ( London , 1608 ) says he had children there also .
#Text=Lady Paulet had only a short imprisonment with the O'Doherties ; but her husband 's death left her in poverty , which was partly relieved out of the Tyrone forfeitures .
#Text=She was alive in 1617 . [ 1 ] [ 8 ]
